    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-03T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-03T13:00:00-05:00" n="246"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d246">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Control (Austria)/11–344:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gallman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-03T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 3, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 3—6:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9549. Department’s 9178, November 2, 7 p.m.<note n="96" xml:id="d246fn96">Not
                        printed; it stated that the Department did not wish its instruction No. 4535
                        of September 14 (printed on page 460), presented to the European Advisory
                        Commission (740.00119 Control (Austria)/11–244).</note> Directive from CCS
                    to SACMED enclosed with Department’s instruction 4535 has not been presented to
                    the EAC.</p>
                <p>On October 4 Strang wrote to Mr. Winant suggesting that they send Gousev
                    identical letters summarizing the pertinent parts of that directive. Strang
                    later withdrew this suggestion in favor of that outlined in Embassy’s 8840
                    (October 17, 6 p.m., Comea 113).<note n="97" xml:id="d246fn97">Not printed; it
                        reported that the British Foreign Office felt that it would be desirable to
                        approach the Russians with a proposal that as soon as any part of Austria
                        was occupied by any of the Allied armies, a tripartite control commission
                        should be set up (740.00119 Control (Austria)/10–1744).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gallman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
